Prpt2:
I did this in codespaces.
Ans:
A Codespace is essentially a cloud development environment connected to a GitHub repository.
When you:
Edit a file in Codespaces
Commit it
the commit is only in the Git repository that the Codespace is attached to.
To get the change into another repository (or into the main branch), you typically need to push and possibly create a Pull Request.




First question: What repository was the Codespace opened from?
Was the Codespace created from:

Option A: The original repository
Example:
owner/main-repo

or

Option B: Your fork
Example:
your-account/main-repo
This distinction is crucial.

Check where your commit went
In the Codespaces terminal, run:
git remote -v
You'll see something like:
origin  https://github.com/your-account/repo.git

or
origin  https://github.com/original-owner/repo.git
This tells us which repository received the commit.







CORRECT:
what if it's option B
If it's Option B (you created the Codespace from your fork), then what you're seeing is normal.
What likely happened

Suppose:
Original repository (main repo)
github.com/MainOwner/project

Your fork
github.com/YourAccount/project
You opened Codespaces from YourAccount/project.
Then you:
Added a file
Committed it
Pushed it

The change went to:
YourAccount/project

NOT to:
MainOwner/project

So when you switch to the account that owns the main repository, you won't see the file there yet.
Why isn't there a Pull Request?
A Pull Request is not automatically created when you commit or push.
GitHub may show a "Compare & pull request" button, but it doesn't always appear immediately or at all.

You often need to create the PR manually.
How to create the Pull Request?

Go to your fork:
YourAccount/project
Then:
Click Pull requests
Click New pull request
Verify:
Base repository = MainOwner/project
Base branch = main
Head repository = YourAccount/project
Compare branch = the branch containing your changes
Click Create pull request

Now the owner of the main repository can review and merge it.








